% Automatisch generiert — Thema: Nuclear Energy
% arg/1 Fakten
arg(pro74).  % [pro] The last to close, in 2013, ran with much reduced emissions, well under 1% of total US CFC emissions.
arg(pro5).  % [pro] Hydro and liquefied gas are the greatest killers, even before coal.
arg(pro5b).  % [pro] Environmentalists do not care about the harms caused by hydro and liquefied gas.
arg(pro55).  % [pro] Any reactor licensable in the West has a substantial containment structure.
arg(pro55b).  % [pro] Most reactors licensable in the West also have a very robust pressure vessel and internal structures.
arg(pro62).  % [pro] Renewables may be used as much as possible.
arg(pro62b).  % [pro] Intrinsic limitations of diffuse, intermittent sources mean that wind and solar can never economically replace coal, gas, and nuclear for large-scale, continuous, reliable supply.
arg(pro2).  % [pro] Some Soviet-designed and built reactors have been a safety concern for many years.
arg(pro2b).  % [pro] Some Soviet-designed and built reactors are much better now than they were in 1986.
arg(con53).  % [con] Nuclear power is a dirty, dangerous, and unnecessary technology.
arg(con53b).  % [con] The world recognized nuclear power as a dirty, dangerous, and unnecessary technology by refusing to give nuclear power greenhouse gas credits during the UN Climate Change talks in The Hague in November 2000.
arg(con119).  % [con] The meltdown at the Fukushima I Nuclear Power Plant was the worst since Chernobyl in Ukraine, 25 years earlier.
arg(con126).  % [con] Renewable energy sources should be used instead.
arg(con72).  % [con] The legacy of environmental contamination has been catastrophic.
arg(con72b).  % [con] The health costs for miners and mines have been catastrophic.
arg(con168).  % [con] Radiation is not easily dealt with, especially in nuclear waste and maintenance materials.
arg(con168b).  % [con] Expensive solutions are needed to contain, control, and shield both people and the environment from radiation's harm.

% att/2 Fakten  (Dung 1995 — binär; Typ/conf aus LLM-Kandidaten als Kommentar)
att(con53, pro74).  % [rebuttal] conf=90 — The con argument labels nuclear power dirty and dangerous, directly contradicting the pro claim of very low emissions.
att(con53b, pro74).  % [rebuttal] conf=85 — Citing the UN’s refusal to grant greenhouse‑gas credits challenges the pro assertion that nuclear emissions are negligible.
att(pro55, con53).  % [rebuttal] conf=80 — Pro55 claims substantial containment, contradicting con53’s claim that nuclear is dangerous
att(pro55, con53b).  % [rebuttal] conf=80 — The safety claim undermines the assertion that nuclear is dirty and dangerous
att(pro55, con126).  % [rebuttal] conf=70 — Pro55’s safety emphasis challenges the recommendation to replace nuclear with renewables
att(pro55, con72).  % [undermining] conf=65 — The claim of robust containment attacks the premise that nuclear causes catastrophic environmental contamination
att(con119, pro2).  % [rebuttal] conf=80 — con119 claims the worst accident was Fukushima, contradicting pro2's claim that Soviet reactors are a safety concern.
att(con53, pro2b).  % [rebuttal] conf=85 — con53 labels nuclear power dirty and dangerous, directly contradicting pro2b's claim that Soviet reactors are now much better.
att(con53b, pro2b).  % [rebuttal] conf=80 — con53b cites international rejection, contradicting pro2b's assertion of improved reactor safety.
att(con119, pro2b).  % [rebuttal] conf=70 — con119 highlights a severe accident, challenging pro2b's claim that Soviet reactors are much better now.
att(con168b, pro2b).  % [undermining] conf=65 — con168b stresses costly containment needs, undermining the claim of improved safety.
att(pro55b, con53).  % [rebuttal] conf=90 — Robust pressure vessels contradict the claim that nuclear power is dangerous
att(pro55b, con53b).  % [rebuttal] conf=90 — Robust pressure vessels undermine the assertion that nuclear power is dirty and dangerous
att(pro55b, con119).  % [undermining] conf=80 — Safety‑focused design challenges the premise that nuclear accidents like Fukushima are inevitable
att(pro62b, con53).  % [rebuttal] conf=92 — Argues nuclear is indispensable, contradicting the claim it is unnecessary
att(pro62b, con53b).  % [rebuttal] conf=92 — Claims renewables cannot replace nuclear, opposing the view that nuclear is unnecessary
att(pro62b, con126).  % [rebuttal] conf=90 — States renewables cannot replace nuclear, opposing the recommendation to use renewables instead